c forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Barnsley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (West Midlands): habitational name from any of several places so called, such as Barnsley (Yorkshire), Barnsley (Gloucestershire), and Barnsleyhall in Bromsgrove (Worcestershire). The places are named from Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, glade, clearing’, preceded by one of several personal names in the genitive case with <i>-es</i>. In Yorkshire, the personal name is <i>Beorn</i>; in Gloucestershire and possibly Worcestershire it is <i>Beornmōd</i>. Compare   Bardsley   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Bardsley","meanings":["habitational name from Bardsley in Ashton under Lyne, Lancashire, so named from the genitive case of the Old English personal name <i>Beornrēd</i> (composed of the elements <i>beorn</i> ‘young warrior’ + <i>rǣd</i> ‘counsel, advice’) + Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","perhaps also a variant of <b>Barnsley</b>, a habitational name from Barnsley in Gloucestershire, since the early records of the placename show variation between spellings in <i>Barnes-</i>, <i>Barndes-</i>, and <i>Bardes-</i>.","English:"]}]},{"name":"Ruth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name (of uncertain derivation) of a Moabite woman who left her own people to remain with her mother-in-law Naomi, and afterwards became the wife of Boaz and an ancestress of David. Her story is told in the book of the Bible that bears her name. It was used among the Puritans in England in the 16th century, partly because of its association with the English vocabulary word <i>ruth</i> meaning ‘compassion’. It has always been popular as a Jewish name, but is now also widespread among people of many different cultures and creeds."],"variants":[{"name":"Rut","meanings":["Biblical.  See  <b>Ruth</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Ruth de Barnsley was born in 1390, in Barnsley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Robert Symes in 1388, in Barnsley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1410, at the age of 20."},"et":{"1390–1410":"1390–1410","1390–1433":"1390–1433","1408–1492":"1408–1492","1410–1492":"1410–1492","about 1408":"umbes 1408","1433":"1433","1410":"1410","about 1410":"umbes 1410","1492":"1492","1408":"1408","1390":"1390","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Barnsley, Yorkshire, England":"Barnsley, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1390–1410":"1390–1410","1390–1433":"1390–1433","1408–1492":"1408–1492","1410–1492":"1410–1492","about 1408":"noin 1408","1433":"1433","1410":"1410","about 1410":"noin 1410","1492":"1492","1408":"1408","1390":"1390","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Barnsley, Yorkshire, England":"Barnsley, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"1390–1410":"1390–1410","1390–1433":"1390–1433","1408–1492":"1408–1492","1410–1492":"1410–1492","about 1408":"environ 1408","1433":"1433","1410":"1410","about 1410":"environ 1410","1492":"1492","1408":"1408","1390":"1390","Yorkshire, England":"Everwyck, Angleterre","Barnsley, Yorkshire, England":"Barnsley, Everwyck, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Ruth de Barnsley est née en 1390, à Barnsley, Everwyck, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a épousé Robert Symes en 1388, à Barnsley, Everwyck, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 2 fils. Elle est décédée en 1410, à l’âge de 20 ans.